WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.520 --> 00:00:05.980
RACHEL BEEN: Hi, I'm Rachel.

00:00:05.980 --> 00:00:07.105
VIKTOR PERSSON: I'm Viktor.

00:00:07.105 --> 00:00:08.370
HANNAH CHO: Hi, I'm Hannah.

00:00:08.370 --> 00:00:09.995
CHRISTIAN ROBERTSON:
And I'm Christian.

00:00:09.995 --> 00:00:12.740
And we're designers that have
been working on this material

00:00:12.740 --> 00:00:16.990
design project, helping our
various products at Google

00:00:16.990 --> 00:00:22.830
to bring the material
designed to it.

00:00:22.830 --> 00:00:29.380
So yesterday in our keynote,
we introduced this concept

00:00:29.380 --> 00:00:30.970
of material design.

00:00:30.970 --> 00:00:35.700
And it's a system that
uses the classical tools

00:00:35.700 --> 00:00:39.770
of print-like
graphic design, along

00:00:39.770 --> 00:00:42.640
with some new
dynamic surfaces that

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:44.690
appeal to our innate
understanding of physics

00:00:44.690 --> 00:00:45.849
and material.

00:00:45.849 --> 00:00:48.390
Today we're going to talk about
how some of the visual design

00:00:48.390 --> 00:00:51.980
concepts help to
define that system.

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:54.440
So, it's not often
recognized about design

00:00:54.440 --> 00:00:56.970
that a good portion of it
happens behind the scenes.

00:00:56.970 --> 00:00:59.460
People don't actually
recognize-- or notice

00:00:59.460 --> 00:01:03.870
actively-- a lot of the choices
that we make as designers.

00:01:03.870 --> 00:01:06.100
Sometimes even people
thinking about visual design

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:07.860
think of it as a
skinny, or covering,

00:01:07.860 --> 00:01:11.390
that's kind of happened
at the very last moment.

00:01:11.390 --> 00:01:15.230
And today we want to show
that beauty isn't skin deep.

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:18.550
We're going to challenge
the idea of visual design

00:01:18.550 --> 00:01:19.610
as a skin.

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:22.510
We want to talk about
the visible and invisible

00:01:22.510 --> 00:01:24.920
structures that make
the material UI work.

00:01:24.920 --> 00:01:27.780
So, we'll show how
invisible grids

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:29.330
can hold the structure together.

00:01:29.330 --> 00:01:31.610
We'll talk about the rules
behind the scenes that

00:01:31.610 --> 00:01:34.570
can help us have better imagery,
and we'll pull the camera back

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:39.500
to show the lighting
and the shadow systems.

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:42.610
So, I'll start with one of the
more invisible, yet visible

00:01:42.610 --> 00:01:46.730
everywhere, design
practices-- typography.

00:01:46.730 --> 00:01:49.280
Typography's a lot more than
just the choice of typeface,

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:51.630
but the letter forms are
a good place to start.

00:01:51.630 --> 00:01:54.910
So, I'll start
talking about Roboto.

00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:56.780
Roboto's a custom
typeface that's

00:01:56.780 --> 00:01:59.620
designed with UI
specifically in mind.

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:02.920
It's a digital native.

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:05.550
And we're using a
new cut of Roboto

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:08.310
as a default typeface
for the material UI.

00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:10.910
We've extensively
reworked the outlines

00:02:10.910 --> 00:02:12.680
to make sure that the
types work, not just

00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:14.970
on mobile and tablet, where
we've started using it,

00:02:14.970 --> 00:02:17.350
but across the
various form factors

00:02:17.350 --> 00:02:20.010
that we're now covering.

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:22.420
So, here's some of the changes.

00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:24.940
This way you'll be able to
pick out the new version

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:31.540
from the old version and impress
your type-obsessed friends.

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:34.600
So, we've calmed down some of
the more unruly characters.

00:02:37.230 --> 00:02:39.904
We also rounded out the
squarer sides on the caps,

00:02:39.904 --> 00:02:41.570
as well as the dots
and the punctuation.

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:47.450
We also completely
redrew the numbers.

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:51.640
And, getting into the details,
we reworked all of the italics

00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:53.720
so that we have better
optical correction

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:54.780
to the diagonal strokes.

00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:58.180
So, if you look at the right
leg of the A versus the left leg

00:02:58.180 --> 00:03:00.795
of the A, you might notice
a very slight difference.

00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:07.689
So, really we treat
almost every single glyph

00:03:07.689 --> 00:03:08.480
to polish and tune.

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:10.813
There's a lot of changes in
the spacing and the metrics.

00:03:10.813 --> 00:03:14.590
I'll spare you the
rest of the details.

00:03:14.590 --> 00:03:18.290
But the typeface itself really
is only a part of typography.

00:03:18.290 --> 00:03:21.882
In fact, if you call a type
designer a typographer,

00:03:21.882 --> 00:03:23.840
he'll point out the
difference between the two.

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:27.480
Typography is the use of type.

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.980
One of our design principles
was to enable content that's

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:33.170
bold and graphic
and intentional.

00:03:33.170 --> 00:03:36.640
And this graphic character
starts with the typography.

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:40.610
In fact, when you actually
look at UI's, it's

00:03:40.610 --> 00:03:42.830
clear that on
almost every screen,

00:03:42.830 --> 00:03:44.320
type is the primary element.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:46.610
So, if I block out just
the type on the right,

00:03:46.610 --> 00:03:48.040
you can see how
the screen really

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:50.180
is structured by the typography.

00:03:50.180 --> 00:03:52.520
In fact, this is
a good exercise--

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:55.180
as you're designing things,
just block it out and just

00:03:55.180 --> 00:03:59.500
look at the type itself, and
see if it contains a structure.

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:02.370
UI design really is typography.

00:04:02.370 --> 00:04:05.549
If we're drawing screens,
whether we know it or not,

00:04:05.549 --> 00:04:06.340
we're typographers.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:11.980
So, this design system
uses really big type

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:14.190
to be expressive,
but also to create

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:15.870
clear hierarchies
of information.

00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:18.769
It's tempting when we're
doing UI design to--

00:04:18.769 --> 00:04:20.209
just because we're
always dealing

00:04:20.209 --> 00:04:23.300
with dynamic content--
it's tempting to just

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:25.620
use the smallest size
possible, because we don't know

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:28.740
in a music player if the band
name is going to be super long,

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:31.050
or we don't know
if in a calculator

00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:33.990
that we're going to have a
calculation that's super long.

00:04:33.990 --> 00:04:37.030
Instead, we can use large
type and then adjust the size

00:04:37.030 --> 00:04:40.260
to accommodate the
copy as needed.

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:42.930
So, it's these
large display sizes

00:04:42.930 --> 00:04:46.680
that are also another
opportunity for branding, where

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:49.530
you might consider
using a custom type,

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:53.070
commissioning a new type,
or even licensing a type.

00:04:53.070 --> 00:04:56.050
It's easier than it might seem.

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:58.290
So, to help us
manage the sizes, we

00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:00.130
use a tool called the
typographic scale.

00:05:00.130 --> 00:05:02.450
This isn't a new idea.

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:05.110
This has been around in
print for a long time.

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:09.390
In fact, the classic
typographic scale

00:05:09.390 --> 00:05:13.560
uses the same math as the
musical pentatonic scale.

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:17.930
It makes sure that there's
enough contrast at each step.

00:05:17.930 --> 00:05:20.450
And what it really
does is it reduces

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:26.240
the amount of distinct
sizes on any one screen,

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:28.580
so that information
is clear, and you

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:29.960
can tell those differences.

00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:32.400
A good rule of thumb is if
you're using more than two

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:34.345
or three sizes on
one screen, you

00:05:34.345 --> 00:05:36.470
should make sure that
there's a good reason for it.

00:05:36.470 --> 00:05:38.050
And if you are
using a size that's

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:41.317
not in the typographic
scale, there

00:05:41.317 --> 00:05:42.900
should be a really
good reason for it.

00:05:45.510 --> 00:05:48.200
Ultimately, though,
the purpose of type

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:50.220
is to serve the content.

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:52.820
It's to help people quickly
parse and communicate

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:54.710
the information.

00:05:54.710 --> 00:05:57.850
And while typography uses up
a good portion of our screen

00:05:57.850 --> 00:06:01.680
real estate in many ways,
it's hard to beat imagery--

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:03.830
photographs and
illustrations-- for impact.

00:06:09.610 --> 00:06:11.450
RACHEL BEEN: So, this
epitomizing phrase

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:13.370
that we've been hearing
a lot of content

00:06:13.370 --> 00:06:16.120
being bold, graphic,
and intentional

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:19.450
is especially apparent with
the use of imagery in product.

00:06:19.450 --> 00:06:23.020
So, we aren't here to encourage
specific aesthetic identities.

00:06:23.020 --> 00:06:25.960
Product brands range from
being subdued and muted

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:27.650
to really bright and colorful.

00:06:27.650 --> 00:06:30.400
And our intention isn't
to prescribe brand.

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:32.720
What we want to encourage
is intentionality and

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:34.990
thoughtfulness concerning
imagery, backed

00:06:34.990 --> 00:06:38.200
by supported principles and best
practices, to make your imagery

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:42.720
and your products come to life
and feel really differentiated.

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:44.920
So, we define the
main principles

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:47.950
of imagery in a
three-part statement--

00:06:47.950 --> 00:06:51.090
be personal, be informative,
and be delightful.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:53.350
So personalize
the imagery, where

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:56.120
applicable, to make your
product feel relevant.

00:06:56.120 --> 00:06:58.400
A degree of intelligence
is automatically

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:02.910
communicated if imagery
accurately reflects the user.

00:07:02.910 --> 00:07:06.730
Inform the user with a visual
translation of information.

00:07:06.730 --> 00:07:09.440
This facilitates
comprehension, and allows

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:12.380
for expedited understanding
of information.

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:13.850
And delight.

00:07:13.850 --> 00:07:17.340
Delight doesn't mean adding
superfluous, fluffy imagery

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:18.990
just to fill space.

00:07:18.990 --> 00:07:21.630
Delight really implies
aesthetic thoughtfulness,

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:24.440
combined with appropriate
contextual use.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:26.830
Delight can make your product
feel not only special,

00:07:26.830 --> 00:07:30.170
but really considerate
of the user.

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:33.460
So, some additional
principles to talk through.

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:35.380
Imagery doesn't have
to be consistently

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:37.380
conspicuous to feel appropriate.

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:39.680
So, this concept of
being immersive, right?

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:41.480
The image above
is a great example

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:43.930
of using imagery to create
context and interest

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:46.960
without overpowering
the primary information.

00:07:46.960 --> 00:07:49.400
The artist portrait is
a textual background

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:51.570
for the interactive
music content,

00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:53.600
which is the primary focus.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:56.480
Use appropriate imagery
hinting at contextualization

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:02.000
to create this type of depth
and texture in your product.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.480
So, be thoughtfully ubiquitous.

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:05.980
So ubiquitous imagery,
similar to delight,

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:09.670
doesn't imply superfluous
use without a rationale.

00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:12.500
Ubiquity here implies
searching for very intentional

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:14.910
visual opportunities,
where previously there

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:16.550
might have been disparities.

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:18.920
So, look for these moments
to introduce imagery

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:24.020
that supports information
personalization and delight.

00:08:24.020 --> 00:08:25.400
So, context.

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:28.670
User should feel that, in every
instance, imagery is visible.

00:08:28.670 --> 00:08:30.570
It feels relevant
and appropriate,

00:08:30.570 --> 00:08:34.142
and not disorienting or
misleading or out of place.

00:08:34.142 --> 00:08:35.850
So, this doesn't always
mean that imagery

00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:38.980
has to be a literal translation
of surrounding information,

00:08:38.980 --> 00:08:39.590
right?

00:08:39.590 --> 00:08:41.860
So, the example
above is perfect.

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:45.060
We don't see the literal facade
of the location of your event,

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:48.630
rather, a feature image from the
location that provides context.

00:08:48.630 --> 00:08:50.700
But context in the
type of context,

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:53.380
such as cuisine, and the
general aesthetic and vibe,

00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:55.880
and potentially even
the time of day.

00:08:55.880 --> 00:08:59.620
So, this contextual accuracy,
combined with really beautiful

00:08:59.620 --> 00:09:02.370
imagery, will create the
best possible experience

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:05.060
for your users.

00:09:05.060 --> 00:09:06.050
So, best practices.

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:09.250
I want to touch really lightly
on some overarching practices

00:09:09.250 --> 00:09:11.970
when creating or
commissioning imagery.

00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:14.670
From an aesthetic
perspective, the main goal

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:16.330
is to create beautiful
images, right?

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:18.920
Your users will feel
inspired and excited to use

00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:20.140
your product.

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:23.050
But beautiful imagery is a
somewhat broad and amorphous

00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:25.900
term, so here's some
overarching tips basically

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:28.810
to point you in the
right direction.

00:09:28.810 --> 00:09:32.450
Ensure that a clear concept
is conveyed in a memorable way

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:34.430
with having a point of focus.

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:36.150
This doesn't
necessarily literally

00:09:36.150 --> 00:09:39.120
translate as a single point
of focus in your image.

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.000
Focus more so
conveys that there's

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.170
clear representation that
won't be lost on the user.

00:09:45.170 --> 00:09:48.250
The user should be able to
parse almost immediately what

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:50.370
the visual represents.

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:52.840
Building narratives take
this concept of focus

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:54.200
and adds some flavor, right?

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:56.920
Is the mood of the image
aspirational, somber,

00:09:56.920 --> 00:09:58.330
celebratory?

00:09:58.330 --> 00:10:01.930
So, this example of Miami is
not only visually informative--

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:04.250
in terms of the location
that the user's travelling

00:10:04.250 --> 00:10:07.540
to-- but it's meant to also be
an aspirational and immersive

00:10:07.540 --> 00:10:10.850
image, creating really
positive connotations with

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:12.400
your location.

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:15.720
So, all imagery is an
editorialized decision, right?

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:18.040
So make intentional
decisions about the narrative

00:10:18.040 --> 00:10:22.050
of your product through imagery.

00:10:22.050 --> 00:10:24.390
I want to end up this section
about imagery speaking

00:10:24.390 --> 00:10:26.900
about some UI
integration, and how

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:30.440
imagery lives within the
material design structure.

00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:31.950
So, scale.

00:10:31.950 --> 00:10:34.220
Not all assets hold
the same visual weight.

00:10:34.220 --> 00:10:36.500
An avatar in an account
switcher is purposely

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:39.830
smaller than a main hero
image, because of information

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:40.980
hierarchy, right?

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:43.540
So, be mindful of these
scale differentiations

00:10:43.540 --> 00:10:46.550
between imagery types such,
as avatars, feature images,

00:10:46.550 --> 00:10:48.980
et cetera, as well a
similar asset types,

00:10:48.980 --> 00:10:51.940
such as thumbnails within
a gallery experience.

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:54.960
Scale in a hierarchy
imply importance,

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:56.810
and not all of your
assets are equal.

00:10:59.696 --> 00:11:02.127
OK, So this seems
obvious, but make sure

00:11:02.127 --> 00:11:04.460
your images are appropriately
sized for their containers

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:06.300
and across platforms.

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:08.390
Material designed
really emphasizes

00:11:08.390 --> 00:11:10.960
large containers, large
real estate, and ideally

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:12.762
these assets should
not appear pixelated

00:11:12.762 --> 00:11:14.220
in your container's
cross-platform.

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:19.250
So also, as you can see
in many of the vignettes,

00:11:19.250 --> 00:11:23.370
a lot of the UI color choices
reflect content, right?

00:11:23.370 --> 00:11:25.050
So, this was spoken
about the keynote.

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:27.460
So, color and imagery
and material design

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:29.460
are really symbiotic.

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:32.720
These bold color
bars, action bars,

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:35.300
should look to a really
intentional color sampling

00:11:35.300 --> 00:11:36.400
story.

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:39.050
This not only creates a
perceived intelligence

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:43.126
concerning the content, but will
make your product feel unique.

00:11:43.126 --> 00:11:45.750
We're building a support library
called Palette, which was also

00:11:45.750 --> 00:11:48.560
mentioned in the keynote, which
is part of the Android support

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:51.500
library and will be part
of the L Preview release.

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:54.230
You will be able to use
it pretty much right away.

00:11:54.230 --> 00:11:55.980
So, what the library
does is automatically

00:11:55.980 --> 00:11:59.990
extract a color palette
based on a particular image.

00:11:59.990 --> 00:12:02.190
We're still iterating
on the algorithms

00:12:02.190 --> 00:12:04.380
and the API's, so
expect improvements

00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:05.526
on this in the future.

00:12:05.526 --> 00:12:06.900
And Viktor is
going to speak more

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:10.530
about color in a little bit.

00:12:10.530 --> 00:12:13.920
So, before I end, I want to
talk about different image types

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:17.140
within the container, so you can
start naming these asset types

00:12:17.140 --> 00:12:19.330
and thinking about
how to use these.

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:21.450
So, avatars and thumbnails.

00:12:21.450 --> 00:12:25.350
Avatars are representations of
entities-- brands and people--

00:12:25.350 --> 00:12:28.150
and most commonly
displayed in circular form.

00:12:28.150 --> 00:12:30.510
Thumbnails allow
the user to peek

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:34.430
into additional visual
content, usually surrounded

00:12:34.430 --> 00:12:37.370
by heterogeneous information,
such as copy, titles, et

00:12:37.370 --> 00:12:38.100
cetera.

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:40.760
They're always actionable
into a more immersive view.

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:44.110
And I think this is the primary
point of what a thumbnail is.

00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:46.080
They're always thinking at more.

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:49.870
So, thumbnails are great assets
to introduce and really tighten

00:12:49.870 --> 00:12:51.075
constrained spaces.

00:12:53.610 --> 00:12:55.990
In material design, we're
introducing two types

00:12:55.990 --> 00:12:59.940
of hero images-- featured
heroes and integrated heroes.

00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:02.550
A feature hero is really
a bold, primary point

00:13:02.550 --> 00:13:05.520
of focus, surrounded by
a heterogeneous layout

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:07.450
with additional information.

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:09.820
But the user's eye
should really look first

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:11.920
to this visual while
still interacting

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:14.210
with the surrounding content.

00:13:14.210 --> 00:13:16.210
Integrated heroes
create a setting

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:18.850
for heterogeneous pieces
of content within a layout.

00:13:18.850 --> 00:13:21.110
They're not the primary
points of focus,

00:13:21.110 --> 00:13:23.800
but more add texture
and depth to the scene.

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:28.500
Gallery images.

00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:31.510
Well, gallery images are the
most bold visual hero images

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:32.910
within your layouts.

00:13:32.910 --> 00:13:36.100
Usually they're
homogeneous layouts,

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:37.880
and these are visual
heroes without

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:40.100
any other visual distractions.

00:13:40.100 --> 00:13:43.410
These are the strongest and most
unobstructed views of imagery

00:13:43.410 --> 00:13:46.470
within your product.

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:50.470
So overall, imagery is a
vital part of material design.

00:13:50.470 --> 00:13:53.900
Thoughtfully incorporating
informative, personal,

00:13:53.900 --> 00:13:55.990
delightful imagery
in your product,

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:58.690
while considering some
of these best practices,

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:00.840
is really going to bring
your product to life,

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:03.530
creating really memorable
and beautifully crafted

00:14:03.530 --> 00:14:05.510
experiences for your user.

00:14:05.510 --> 00:14:07.880
So as I mentioned
before, imagery is really

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:09.849
united with color,
so Viktor's going

00:14:09.849 --> 00:14:11.390
to come up and speak
more about that.

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:17.770
VIKTOR PERSSON: Let's
talk about color

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:20.926
and how to use color to enhance
your branding and your user

00:14:20.926 --> 00:14:21.425
experience.

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:28.000
The material design system
enables bold and intentional

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.740
use of color, and I
figured the best way

00:14:30.740 --> 00:14:32.970
to show you this is to
design an example app.

00:14:35.970 --> 00:14:37.720
When choosing your
color theme, you

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:42.210
should really use
your brand colors.

00:14:42.210 --> 00:14:45.040
If you happen not to
have brand colors,

00:14:45.040 --> 00:14:48.620
we've actually created an
extensive color palette

00:14:48.620 --> 00:14:50.730
with beautiful colors
that we use ourselves

00:14:50.730 --> 00:14:52.190
to define our own color themes.

00:14:55.290 --> 00:15:00.030
This example app's primary
color will be indigo blue.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:01.890
This is the main
color of the app.

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:04.640
So, if your brand color
is red, for example,

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:07.850
this color should really be red.

00:15:07.850 --> 00:15:12.800
Bold and immersive use of
color is strongly encouraged.

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:14.990
With that said, not all
screens are the same.

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:22.230
Density of color depends
on the density of content.

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:26.500
So, in a screen with
very little content,

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:30.187
it enables bolder use of
color than, let's say,

00:15:30.187 --> 00:15:31.270
a content-heavy list view.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.320
Here are a few good
examples of how

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:44.910
bold color is applied
in more generous ways.

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:48.560
It brings to life otherwise
utilitarian experiences,

00:15:48.560 --> 00:15:51.060
such as the
calculator, or how it

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:53.140
can complement
immersive imagery.

00:15:56.560 --> 00:16:00.420
OK, let's move on and choose
the accent color for this app.

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:02.720
This color is to
provide contrast

00:16:02.720 --> 00:16:09.020
for important buttons, UI
elements, and components.

00:16:09.020 --> 00:16:10.880
Don't choose an
accent color that

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:13.530
doesn't provide enough contrast.

00:16:13.530 --> 00:16:15.490
This color is really
supposed to pop.

00:16:18.890 --> 00:16:23.140
Here are a few good examples of
how an accent color can provide

00:16:23.140 --> 00:16:26.965
the right focus and attention
to certain areas or components.

00:16:31.970 --> 00:16:33.660
If you've chosen an
accent color that

00:16:33.660 --> 00:16:38.310
doesn't work in certain
circumstances, don't worry.

00:16:38.310 --> 00:16:41.330
You can always fall back
to a lighter or darker tint

00:16:41.330 --> 00:16:42.350
of that same color.

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:48.230
Pull those colors
together, and you'll

00:16:48.230 --> 00:16:51.240
get your basic color theme.

00:16:51.240 --> 00:16:54.670
We are very happy that we've
baked this into the Android

00:16:54.670 --> 00:16:56.770
platform and made it
a lot easier for you

00:16:56.770 --> 00:17:00.200
guys to define your
own color theme.

00:17:00.200 --> 00:17:02.910
And remember, the
strongest tool we

00:17:02.910 --> 00:17:08.369
have to unite a user experience
across multiple platforms

00:17:08.369 --> 00:17:09.530
and devices is color.

00:17:13.950 --> 00:17:16.450
So, we talked about
the design principles.

00:17:16.450 --> 00:17:18.670
We talked about typography.

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:22.130
We talked about
imagery and color.

00:17:22.130 --> 00:17:24.119
Let's bring them all
together and design

00:17:24.119 --> 00:17:25.839
a beautiful and consistent UI.

00:17:29.060 --> 00:17:33.280
As Zach mentioned earlier
in the direction talk,

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:35.210
over the course
of design history,

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:40.320
there have emerged
rules and guidelines

00:17:40.320 --> 00:17:44.450
that we as designers are really,
really excited about that we

00:17:44.450 --> 00:17:50.030
baked this in and included in
the material design system.

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:54.740
So here a few examples of
these rules and guidelines.

00:17:54.740 --> 00:17:56.770
So, structural elements
in the material

00:17:56.770 --> 00:18:00.930
designed system
aligns to an 8dp grid.

00:18:00.930 --> 00:18:05.449
This will provide consistency,
harmony, and rhythm

00:18:05.449 --> 00:18:06.115
to your designs.

00:18:09.300 --> 00:18:12.400
Content should follow
a set of key lines.

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:16.900
16dp and 72dp on
mobile, 24dp and 80dp

00:18:16.900 --> 00:18:21.090
on tablets, desktops,
and larger screen sizes.

00:18:21.090 --> 00:18:24.250
As you can see here, it
really orders the content

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:26.840
and structures the
content so that it becomes

00:18:26.840 --> 00:18:31.330
more predictable, and your
user can read this content

00:18:31.330 --> 00:18:32.780
a lot easier and faster.

00:18:36.040 --> 00:18:39.970
Increments is an
excellent tool, or help,

00:18:39.970 --> 00:18:44.130
to determine the size of
larger structural elements,

00:18:44.130 --> 00:18:48.020
such as the app bar
or the nav drawer.

00:18:48.020 --> 00:18:52.340
The increments are based on the
standard app bar height, which

00:18:52.340 --> 00:18:56.910
is 56dp on mobile and
64dp on tablets, desktops,

00:18:56.910 --> 00:18:58.085
and larger screen sizes.

00:19:02.550 --> 00:19:06.640
When setting your type,
make sure to align it

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:09.420
to a 4dp baseline grid.

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:12.170
This will make your
typography and content easier

00:19:12.170 --> 00:19:16.380
to read and make it
aesthetically more pleasing.

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:18.940
I'm sure everyone
here at some point

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:21.690
has seen a design or
an app and just felt

00:19:21.690 --> 00:19:25.040
like, oh, there's something off.

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:30.510
Not aligning your type to
a consistent baseline grid

00:19:30.510 --> 00:19:33.670
might very well have been
what was the problem there.

00:19:38.580 --> 00:19:42.110
Let's go back to our example
app again and apply these rules

00:19:42.110 --> 00:19:45.330
and guides that we've
incorporated in the material

00:19:45.330 --> 00:19:47.300
design system.

00:19:47.300 --> 00:19:50.900
This is going to be a fairly
straightforward list view app,

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:53.090
but I wanted to enable
bolder use of color,

00:19:53.090 --> 00:19:54.250
as I talked about before.

00:19:54.250 --> 00:19:57.115
So, I made the app bar
3x of the increment.

00:20:01.020 --> 00:20:05.800
When designing your layouts,
start thinking in blocks.

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:09.460
This is extremely helpful, and
will make your design process

00:20:09.460 --> 00:20:13.260
easier, faster, and,
I would say, better.

00:20:13.260 --> 00:20:17.250
For this app, I'm going to
use an avatar to the left,

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:19.830
with two lines of
text next to it.

00:20:19.830 --> 00:20:22.450
So for that I'll
use a block of 72dp.

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:31.280
When placing in your content,
as I said, follow the key lines.

00:20:31.280 --> 00:20:35.640
In this example, the
16dp and 24dp key line

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:38.790
is reserved for
icons and avatars.

00:20:38.790 --> 00:20:41.440
That means that your
typography and text

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:45.680
should follow the 72dp
and 82dp key line.

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:48.970
As you can clearly see,
it provides a structure

00:20:48.970 --> 00:20:50.690
and a predictability
to the eye that

00:20:50.690 --> 00:20:53.080
is just very user-friendly
and easy to scan.

00:20:56.320 --> 00:21:00.480
Last but not least,
remember the baseline grid.

00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:02.154
Align your typography
to the baseline

00:21:02.154 --> 00:21:03.570
grid to achieve
better typography.

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:08.130
And there we have it.

00:21:08.130 --> 00:21:11.690
By using these-- I would
say almost magical tools

00:21:11.690 --> 00:21:14.150
and guidelines, as well
as fundamental tools

00:21:14.150 --> 00:21:18.900
and guidelines, we've created a
bold, beautiful, user-friendly

00:21:18.900 --> 00:21:22.040
UI over multiple platforms
and form factors.

00:21:24.461 --> 00:21:25.960
Over to Hannah, who
is going to talk

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:28.543
about surface and dimension.

00:21:28.543 --> 00:21:30.467
HANNAH CHO: Thank you.

00:21:30.467 --> 00:21:32.872
[APPLAUSE]

00:21:32.872 --> 00:21:35.770
HANNAH CHO: Yay.

00:21:35.770 --> 00:21:38.260
OK, so Viktor just went
over on the details

00:21:38.260 --> 00:21:39.730
of how to create a layout.

00:21:39.730 --> 00:21:41.970
In material design, you
have to also consider

00:21:41.970 --> 00:21:45.980
how these elements live and
move in 3D space, not just 2D.

00:21:45.980 --> 00:21:49.380
We can model how people perceive
material in our UI to group

00:21:49.380 --> 00:21:51.200
and structure our content.

00:21:51.200 --> 00:21:54.570
The use of surface and material
can solve spatial issues,

00:21:54.570 --> 00:21:57.920
and they're not meant to
be used just as decoration.

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:00.209
So, in material design,
we use this technique

00:22:00.209 --> 00:22:01.250
to give our UI dimension.

00:22:03.830 --> 00:22:06.080
So, we interact with
physical objects every day.

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:07.740
The tangible
qualities and shadows

00:22:07.740 --> 00:22:10.440
help us to quickly
understand affordances.

00:22:10.440 --> 00:22:13.200
So, we were inspired by the
tactile qualities of paper

00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:15.350
and studied how light
interacts with the material

00:22:15.350 --> 00:22:16.900
to creator our shadows.

00:22:16.900 --> 00:22:19.120
We didn't just apply
this approach to our UI.

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:21.020
We actually did
a lot of studies.

00:22:21.020 --> 00:22:24.354
We recreated our icons by
folding actual pieces of paper

00:22:24.354 --> 00:22:26.270
and placing them in
different lighting set-ups

00:22:26.270 --> 00:22:29.600
to understand exactly how those
shadows should be constructed.

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:32.010
These are actual photos that
we studied-- the studies

00:22:32.010 --> 00:22:34.260
that we did-- and you can
see all the cool things that

00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:35.970
are happening in these photos.

00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:38.424
There's soft ambient
shadows caused by the light,

00:22:38.424 --> 00:22:40.590
and you can see how the
light is being reflected off

00:22:40.590 --> 00:22:44.100
the paper, causing subtle
highlights on the edges.

00:22:44.100 --> 00:22:46.170
This process allowed
us understand

00:22:46.170 --> 00:22:48.280
how we can
realistically recreate

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:51.690
the subtle highlights and
consistent shadows in a layout.

00:22:54.560 --> 00:22:57.910
So, how do we
create the shadows?

00:22:57.910 --> 00:23:05.730
There's supposed
to be animation OK.

00:23:05.730 --> 00:23:06.820
Imagine this animating.

00:23:06.820 --> 00:23:08.670
So, how do we create
these shadows?

00:23:08.670 --> 00:23:10.810
In order to make our
shadows feel real,

00:23:10.810 --> 00:23:13.520
we needed to create a
technically audacious system

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:15.910
that did more than just
pre-render a static drop

00:23:15.910 --> 00:23:16.660
shadow.

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:18.640
So, with our amazing
engineering team,

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:21.860
they built a system that
uses real-time soft shadows.

00:23:21.860 --> 00:23:25.030
The shadows are projected from
a virtual light source that

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:27.250
are also being rendered
through a camera.

00:23:27.250 --> 00:23:30.550
So, this allowed us to have
consistent set of transforms

00:23:30.550 --> 00:23:32.757
that keeps this illusion
alive as the users move

00:23:32.757 --> 00:23:34.465
from a screen to
screen, or between apps.

00:23:38.550 --> 00:23:40.470
This is the virtual
light source animation

00:23:40.470 --> 00:23:43.400
that didn't play earlier, and
there's the virtual camera.

00:23:49.070 --> 00:23:50.740
So, these two types
of shadows make up

00:23:50.740 --> 00:23:53.180
the shadow layers we
use in material design.

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:55.740
The key shadow creates
the illusion of depth,

00:23:55.740 --> 00:23:59.220
while the ambient shadow defines
the form of the material.

00:23:59.220 --> 00:24:01.890
Together, the shadows create
a halo around the material

00:24:01.890 --> 00:24:04.905
without needing to use a hard
stroke to create an outline.

00:24:16.610 --> 00:24:17.740
Aha, animation.

00:24:17.740 --> 00:24:18.240
OK.

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:21.570
Shadows also create the
separation between surfaces.

00:24:21.570 --> 00:24:24.570
What this means is that the
depth of our shadow changes

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:25.920
scale and focus.

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:27.710
So, elements closer
to the camera

00:24:27.710 --> 00:24:30.300
have more diffuse shadows,
and elements further away

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:34.510
from the camera, the shadow
becomes more focused.

00:24:34.510 --> 00:24:36.320
So, the strength of
the shadow really

00:24:36.320 --> 00:24:39.634
determines the perceived
depth of our material.

00:24:39.634 --> 00:24:41.050
You can really see
the differences

00:24:41.050 --> 00:24:43.700
between the perceived depth
in these two examples.

00:24:43.700 --> 00:24:45.560
The scale of the
shadow helps to show

00:24:45.560 --> 00:24:48.080
where these elements
live spatially.

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:50.680
In the example on the left,
the surface of the dialogue

00:24:50.680 --> 00:24:52.490
is closer to the
camera, resulting

00:24:52.490 --> 00:24:55.300
in a softer shadow, where as
in an example on the right,

00:24:55.300 --> 00:24:56.940
cars are further
away from the camera,

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:58.700
resulting in a more
defined shadow.

00:25:02.070 --> 00:25:03.655
And, because our
shadows are dynamic,

00:25:03.655 --> 00:25:05.520
they also move in
space, depending

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:08.890
on the location of the material
as the camera is fixed.

00:25:08.890 --> 00:25:12.040
Like this example, when you
start to see the shadows

00:25:12.040 --> 00:25:14.840
move from the left
and right and how

00:25:14.840 --> 00:25:16.480
it's moving below
the surface, you

00:25:16.480 --> 00:25:19.920
can clearly see how the surface
is being brought to life.

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:21.570
All of these details
might be subtle,

00:25:21.570 --> 00:25:24.260
but it really makes up
the whole experience.

00:25:24.260 --> 00:25:26.560
The shadows provide
a familiar visual cue

00:25:26.560 --> 00:25:29.910
that we just
naturally understand.

00:25:29.910 --> 00:25:31.640
So, all of the
theory behind shadows

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:33.930
may sound super complex,
but don't worry.

00:25:33.930 --> 00:25:36.050
They're all built
into the system.

00:25:36.050 --> 00:25:38.000
Designers can download
an illustrator file

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:39.162
that has the shadows.

00:25:39.162 --> 00:25:41.120
And you guys can use them
to design your mocks,

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:43.270
but don't use them
to make assets.

00:25:43.270 --> 00:25:45.360
Engineers can simply
set the z-height value

00:25:45.360 --> 00:25:48.450
and get system shadows for
Polymer and Android for free.

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:53.280
Now that we've covered
how the shadows are built,

00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:55.970
let's look at some examples
of how they are used.

00:25:55.970 --> 00:25:57.980
A good way to think
about these surfaces

00:25:57.980 --> 00:26:00.310
is that they're tools
to help focus attention

00:26:00.310 --> 00:26:01.940
and create emphasis.

00:26:01.940 --> 00:26:04.010
So FAB-- a floating
action button--

00:26:04.010 --> 00:26:06.360
is a great example of
how we use surfaces

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:08.300
to help focus attention.

00:26:08.300 --> 00:26:11.150
Just by virtue of being its
own separate piece of material,

00:26:11.150 --> 00:26:13.390
FABS have the most
prominence in our UI,

00:26:13.390 --> 00:26:16.270
and this really helps
to promote the action.

00:26:16.270 --> 00:26:18.580
A dialogue with
another great example.

00:26:18.580 --> 00:26:21.190
Bringing a dialogue to a
surface creates an isolation

00:26:21.190 --> 00:26:23.250
of the content, and
allows the users

00:26:23.250 --> 00:26:27.970
to focus on things that require
either a decision or action.

00:26:27.970 --> 00:26:30.570
Here's a bad example of how
you could overuse shadows

00:26:30.570 --> 00:26:32.440
and dimensions in your layout.

00:26:32.440 --> 00:26:34.010
Having a surface
on surface in this

00:26:34.010 --> 00:26:37.310
is layout distracts from
being able to focus attention.

00:26:37.310 --> 00:26:40.290
So, if you see that your design
requires too many layers,

00:26:40.290 --> 00:26:43.220
then maybe your
content is too complex.

00:26:43.220 --> 00:26:46.160
Shadows should really be used
to determine the surface where

00:26:46.160 --> 00:26:47.940
you want your primary
content to be.

00:26:55.410 --> 00:26:58.380
Surfaces are powerful grouping
tools for our content.

00:26:58.380 --> 00:27:01.060
Like in this cars example,
we can use surfaces

00:27:01.060 --> 00:27:04.620
to group complex content
into a digestible view.

00:27:04.620 --> 00:27:06.520
This creates a
visual system that

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:08.180
keeps our layout
clean and beautiful

00:27:08.180 --> 00:27:10.390
by organizing our
type and imagery,

00:27:10.390 --> 00:27:12.660
especially with complex data.

00:27:12.660 --> 00:27:14.520
But, we want to
avoid using surfaces

00:27:14.520 --> 00:27:16.180
when it's not necessary.

00:27:16.180 --> 00:27:19.490
